{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"949"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/949"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.14,0.3,0.41,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68018"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/949"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"949"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53483"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"354"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"9060"},{"type":"tags","id":"9064"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"717"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36519"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68018"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 35-year-old man presents with a three year history of worsening dysphagia and after various investigations is diagnosed with Chicago Type I achalasia. High resolution manometry confirms impaired relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter and no peristaltic activity in the body of the oesophagus. He is being counselled on management options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to provide him with effective long-term relief of his dysphagia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Botulinum toxin injection","Balloon dilatation","Peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM)","Laparoscopic cardiomyotomy and partial fundoplication","Oesophagectomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith the development of high-resolution manometry, a more subtle distinction can be made between the various types of achalasia. The Chicago classification of motility disorders describes three variants for achalasia, where Type I details the classical changes of a raised lower oesophageal sphincter pressure and no peristalsis in the body of the oesophagus. Treatment in this group of patients is aimed at reducing or abolishing the lower oesophageal sphincter, to allow food to \u0027drain\u0027 out of the oesophagus. Botulinus toxin can produce good short-term results, but its durability is measured in months. Balloon dilatation can give effective long-term results - but can be complicated in about 15% of patients with troublesome gastro-oesophageal reflux. Another problem with balloon dilatation is the frequent need for repeated procedures and the risk of the patient then requiring surgery and the technical challenges from the resultant scar tissue. Oesophagectomy is reserved for those with end-stage disease - and in selected patients, can give excellent relief of symptoms. The peroral endoscopic myotomy (POEM) is a relatively new endoscopic approach to the division of the lower oesophageal sphincter and probably is most applicable to Chicago Type III cases (those with spastic contractions of the body of the oesophagus). Current experience with POEM suggests a 50% risk of long term proton pump inhibitor use to control gastro-oesophageal reflux symptoms brought about by the procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic cardiomyotomy\u003C/strong\u003E will produce good symptomatic relief of the troublesome dysphagia and regurgitation associated with this type of achalasia. The addition of a partial fundoplication will minimise any gastro-oesophageal reflux.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A laparoscopic cardiomyotomy can provide good long-term treatment for patients with achalasia."],"references":["Patel DA, Lappas BM, Vaezi MF. An Overview of Achalasia and Its Subtypes. Gastroenterology \u0026 Hepatology 2017; 13:411-21. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5572971/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53483"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"949"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53483"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-08T14:19:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-19T21:12:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"949"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68018"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":